---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Dr. Liz Blower | Doctoral College UK" description="Profile of Dr. Liz Blower, Academic Lead for Operations &amp; Finance at DCUK and doctoral supervisor in professional education and researcher wellbeing.">

  <section class="py-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">

      <a href="/supervisors" class="text-accent hover:underline text-sm mb-8 inline-block">&larr; Back to Supervisors</a>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-12">

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="md:col-span-1">
          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-1">Dr. Liz Blower</h1>
            <p class="text-accent font-medium mb-4">Academic Lead for Operations &amp; Finance</p>
            <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-muted">
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Specialisms:</strong> Professional Education, Doctoral Wellbeing, Qualitative Methodology</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Methods:</strong> Qualitative (IPA, narrative inquiry, case study)</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Active researchers:</strong> 3</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Capacity:</strong> Open to new enquiries</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Research Interests</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>Wellbeing in professional doctoral education</li>
              <li>Identity formation and professional transitions</li>
              <li>Pastoral support frameworks in HE</li>
              <li>The experience of part-time doctoral study</li>
              <li>Peer learning and peer support in postgraduate contexts</li>
              <li>Qualitative methods in education research</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Qualifications</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>PhD, Education, University of Birmingham</li>
              <li>MA Educational Psychology, University of Manchester</li>
              <li>BA (Hons) Psychology, University of York</li>
              <li>Fellow, Higher Education Academy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Main content -->
        <div class="md:col-span-2 space-y-8">

          <div>
            <p class="section-label mb-3">Biography</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About Liz</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-muted">
              <p>Dr. Liz Blower is the Academic Lead for Operations &amp; Finance at DCUK, with overall responsibility for researcher wellbeing, pastoral support, and the quality of the doctoral journey from induction to completion. She joined DCUK after an academic career spanning psychology, educational research, and postgraduate student support at two Russell Group universities.</p>
              <p>Liz's research background is in the psychology of learning and professional development, with a particular focus on wellbeing in the context of doctoral study. Her doctoral thesis examined the lived experience of part-time doctoral researchers — the psychological challenges of managing doctoral identity alongside professional and personal responsibilities, and what institutions can do to support researchers without infantilising them or increasing their dependency.</p>
              <p>This research has directly shaped DCUK's pastoral framework. Under Liz's leadership, DCUK operates an annual pastoral review for every researcher, maintains an open-door approach to researcher welfare concerns, and has developed peer learning structures specifically designed to reduce the isolation that part-time doctoral study can generate. The peer learning circle model that Liz designed for DCUK has been adopted by several other institutions following a published case study in 2023.</p>
              <p>As a supervisor, Liz works with researchers whose topics connect to professional education, wellbeing in organisational or educational contexts, and qualitative approaches to studying human experience. She is particularly interested in working with professionals from healthcare, education, and social care contexts who are examining the wellbeing and development of the people they serve or lead.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Selected Publications</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Blower, E. (2024). 'I never felt like a proper researcher': Identity threat and professional doctoral study. <em>Studies in Higher Education</em>, 49(3), 445–461.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">An IPA study examining the experience of impostor syndrome and identity uncertainty in part-time professional doctoral students, with implications for institutional support design.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Blower, E. (2023). Peer learning circles in professional doctorate programmes: A case study of design and impact. <em>Teaching in Higher Education</em>, 28(5), 1012–1029.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A case study of DCUK's peer learning circle model, examining design principles, participant experience, and impact on researcher wellbeing and academic progress.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, P. &amp; Blower, E. (2022). Wellbeing and performance in knowledge-intensive work: A systematic review. <em>International Journal of Human Resource Management</em>, 33(12), 2401–2428.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">Co-authored systematic review of evidence on wellbeing-performance relationships in professional and knowledge-intensive work environments.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Blower, E. (2020). Managing emotional labour in doctoral supervision: A qualitative study of supervisory practice. <em>Higher Education Research &amp; Development</em>, 39(6), 1148–1162.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A qualitative exploration of the emotional dimensions of doctoral supervision, examining how supervisors manage the pastoral aspects of their supervisory role alongside academic guidance.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Current Researchers</h2>
            <p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm">Dr. Blower currently supervises three doctoral researchers. Their work includes a study of occupational burnout in NHS nursing leadership, an examination of the professional identity of newly-qualified social workers, and a narrative inquiry into the experience of retirees undertaking professional development in later life.</p>
            <div class="card">
              <p class="text-sm text-muted">Dr. Blower is open to enquiries from researchers whose work touches on wellbeing, professional identity, or the experience of learning and development in professional contexts. She is particularly interested in qualitative and interpretive approaches. Please contact us to discuss your research interests.</p>
              <div class="mt-4">
                <a href="/connect" class="btn-primary text-sm">Enquire about supervision</a>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
